{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5269","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:46 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:46 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Abbreviations are very common in Literary Tibetan. They are of two kinds: phonic and graphic. The former usually occur only in the case of quadrisyllabic expressions, and consist of omitting the second and fourth syllables.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱང་སེམས་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་</span> “Bodhisattva” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དེ་གཤེགས་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དེ་བཞིན་གཤེགས་པ་</span> “Tathāgata” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐེག་ཆེན་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོ་</span> “Mahāyāna” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཕྱག་རྡོར་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཕྱག་ན་རྡོ་རྗེ་</span> “The bodhisattva Vajrapāṇi (or Chakna Dorjé)”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགེ་སློབ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགེ་རྒན་དང་སློབ་མ་</span> “Master and disciple(s)” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞིང་འབྲོག་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞིང་པ་དང་འབྲོག་པ་</span> “Farmers and nomads”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The same principle applies in the spoken language for abridging personal names of four syllables:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཚེ་རྡོར་</span> Tsedor = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཚེ་རིང་རྡོ་རྗེ་</span> Tsering Dorjé</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཀྲ་དཔལ་</span> Trapel = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཀྲ་ཤིས་དཔལ་ལྡན་</span> Trashi Penden</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆོས་རྒྱམ་</span> Chögyam = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆོས་ཀྱི་རྒྱ་མཚོ་</span> Chökyi Gyatso (or Gyamtso)</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསོད་སྒྲོན་</span> Södrön = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསོད་ནམས་སྒྲོལ་མ་</span> Sönam Drölma</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Note that in some cases, a resyllabification occurs whereby the prefixed or the superscribed letter of the following syllable is interpreted as the final of the preceding syllable. The written orthography records this phenomenon. For example, the last letter in Chögyam or Tsedor belongs in fact to the fourth syllable (that has been omitted), respectively <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མཚོ་</span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྗེ་</span>.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Graphic abbreviations consist of using special signs to replace a group of letters. The following are the most common:</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The circle<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"> ༚</span>, written above a letter, replaces the suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མ</span>:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལཾ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལམ་</span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཊ་</span> (reversed <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཏ་</span>) substitutes for the suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གས་</span>:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལཊ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལགས་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལེཊ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལེགས་ </span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">There are also abbreviations in which two syllables are graphically compacted into a single syllable:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བོུ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བུ་མོ་</span> “Girl”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཚོུ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆུ་ཚོད་</span> “Hour”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཀྲིས་བདེ་ལེཊ་</span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཀྲ་ཤིས་བདེ་ལེགས་</span></li> </ul>","title":""}]}
